english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Six Friends
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Kim Kyung-ji of Yeongga named his hall the "Hall of Four Friends," drawing upon the Master Kangjeol's teaching of snow, moon, wind, and flowers. He asked me to expound upon its meaning, but I was disinclined to study Kangjeol's philosophy and besides had no leisure, so I put off responding for a long time. Later, when he dwelt in Yeohung, he sent me a letter saying: "Now that I am at my mother's home, the beauty of rivers and mountains consoles me morning and evening. It is not merely snow, moon, wind, and flowers alone. Therefore I have added rivers and mountains to these four, calling them the Six Friends. Master, would you not teach me of this?"

    I replied: "My decline and illness have long persisted. Heaven's seasons shift above, yet I remain bewildered. Earth's forms crumble below, yet I perceive nothing. Master Kangjeol's learning runs deep in number and pattern. Though you crown it now with rivers and mountains to show distinction from Kangjeol, the Six Dragons and Six Voids of the Book of Changes are the very source from which Kangjeol's learning springs—thus your Six Friends too return to Kangjeol in the end.

    Yet since I have said I am unwilling to study his way, should I have nothing else to say? Hear then: Mountains are what the humane delight in. Upon seeing a mountain, my humanity is preserved. Rivers are what the wise delight in. Upon seeing a river, my wisdom is preserved. Snow, pressing down the winter's cold, preserves the harmony of my vital breath. The moon, rising in the night, brings light and preserves the peace of my form. Wind comes from eight directions, each in its season, and thus I act without delusion. Flowers gather in four seasons, each by their kind, and thus I maintain the proper order.

    Moreover, Kim Kyung-ji's spirit is clear and luminous, without a speck of dust or dross. And where he dwells—with bright mountains and green waters, as one might call them a polished mirror and a brocade screen—there is nothing unseemly. Snow upon a solitary boat, wrapped in a rain cloak, becomes yet more fair. The moon reflected in a high tower with wine cup becomes yet more fair. Wind crossing a fishing line becomes ever more crystalline. Flowers upon a reading table become ever more profound. The beauty of the four seasons reaches its ultimate expression, woven between river and mountain. In his leisure time attending his mother, Kim Kyung-ji lets his boat drift upon the river and climbs the mountains in straw sandals. He stands before the clear wind counting falling petals. He treads through snow seeking out monks. He faces the moon inviting guests. The joys of all four seasons reach their ultimate expression.

    Kim Kyung-ji stands alone in our age, unmatched by others.

    Yet friends are those of kindred spirit. If one seeks ancient sages as friends, they are not merely one or two. If one seeks friends among the present, are not men like myself quite numerous? Yet Kim Kyung-ji takes only these six—rivers and mountains, snow and moon, wind and flowers. Truly he stands alone in our age, unmatched by others.

    And yet—heaven and earth are our parents; all things share our nature. Wherever we go, is it not a friend we find? How much more so when studying the mountain of Great Gathering and the water of Repeated Hardship, gaining knowledge and practice—these become true friends indeed.

    Thus I write this Record of the Hall of Six Friends.
  footnotes:
    - 'Master Kangjeol (康節): A reference to Shao Yong (邵雍, 1011-1077), a Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Song Dynasty known for his cosmological system based on number and pattern (象數). His famous phrase about the four friends of contemplation is: snow, moon, wind, and flowers.'
    - 'Six Dragons and Six Voids: Cosmological concepts from the Book of Changes (I Ching) representing the dynamic principles underlying reality and the hexagrams'' structure.'
    - 'Great Gathering and Repeated Hardship: References to hexagrams 26 (大蓄) and 29 (習坎) from the Book of Changes, here used symbolically to represent the study of mountains and waters as paths to self-cultivation.'
